  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "**What happened**:\r\nWhen deleting a service, graceful termination does not work:\r\n- If no RS is in the graceful termination list, the VS will be deleted and traffic from existing connections will be blackholed\r\n- If an RS is in graceful termination, VS deletion will be postponed, but the ClusterIP (and others) will be unbound from kube-ipvs0 so traffic will be blackholed\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\nGraceful termination to work, and no traffic blackholing\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\nNo pod in graceful termination:\r\n1- Create a service backed by a deployment\r\n2- Establish a long lived connection from a pod\r\n3- Delete the service\r\n=> VS will be deleted, addresses unbound and traffic from the pod will be blackholed\r\n\r\nOne pod in graceful termination:\r\n1- Create a service backed by a deployment\r\n2- Establish a long lived connection from a pod\r\n3- Delete a pod from the deployment backing the service\r\n3- Delete the service\r\n=> VS will not be deleted, but addresses will be unbound and traffic from the client pod will be blackholed\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\nTwo reasons for this issue:\r\n- `cleanLegacyService` does not trigger graceful termination for current real servers\r\n- `cleanLegacyBindAddr` is always called and does not take into the graceful termination list\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`): kube-proxy `v1.13.0-alpha.3`\r\n- OS (e.g. from /etc/os-release): `Ubuntu 18.04.1 LTS`\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`): `Linux ip-10-128-212-113 4.15.0-1023-aws #23-Ubuntu SMP Mon Sep 24 16:31:06 UTC 2018 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux`\r\n\r\n/area ipvs\r\n/sig network\r\n/kind bug\r\n\r\n/assign @m1093782566 ",
